	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />To make a VRC6 game, first you need a supply of VRC6 chips. There are only two ways to get one of those: <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>Rip open one of the dwindling supply of VRC6 games for each copy that you plan to make. </li><li>Decap and photomicrograph a VRC6, write out its netlist in Verilog, and get an ASIC synthesized and fabricated. </li></ol>
<br />If you just want to listen to your NSFs, a PowerPak through the right 72-to-60-pin converter might be the easiest way to do so on a time==money basis.
<br />
<br />I'd imagine that most people with a system capable of playing Famicom expansion sound can read Japanese because they bought a Famicom while living in Japan. (Those who imported a Famicom or modded their NES are a slim minority, despite their overrepresentation here and on NintendoAge.) If you can't read Japanese, stick with normal carts. Those are easy to make; kits for NROM (#000), CNROM (#003), UNROM (#002), BNROM (#034), AOROM (#007), and S*ROM (#001) are available from retrousb.com.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


